ent view.","205_NAME":"RESET_CONTENT","206":"Partial Content","206_CLASS":"2xx","206_MESSAGE":"The server is delivering only part of the resource (byte serving) due to a range header sent by the client.","206_NAME":"PARTIAL_CONTENT","207":"Multi Status","207_CLASS":"2xx","207_MESSAGE":"The message body that follows is by default an XML message and can contain a number of separate response codes, depending on how many sub-requests were made.","207_NAME":"MULTI_STATUS","208":"Already Reported","208_CLASS":"2xx","208_MESSAGE":"The members of a DAV binding have already been enumerated in a preceding part of the (multistatus) response, and are not being included again.","208_NAME":"ALREADY_REPORTED","226":"IM Used","226_CLASS":"2xx","226_MESSAGE":"The server has fulfilled a request for the resource, and the response is a representation of the result of one or more instance-manipulations applied to the current instance.","226_NAME":"IM_USED","300":"Multiple Choices","300_CLASS":"3xx","300_MESSAGE":"Indicates multiple options for the resource from which the client may choose.","300_NAME":"MULTIPLE_CHOICES","301":"Moved Permanently","301_CLASS":"3xx","301_MESSAGE":"This and all future requests should be directed to the given URI.","301_NAME":"MOVED_PERMANENTLY","302":"Found","302_CLASS":"3xx","302_MESSAGE":"This is an example of industry practice contradicting the standard. The HTTP/1.0 specification (RFC 1945) required the client to perform a temporary redirect (the original describing phrase was \"Moved Temporarily\"), but popular browsers implemented 302 with the functionality of a 303 See Other. Therefore, HTTP/1.1 added status codes 303 and 307 to distinguish between the two behaviours.","302_NAME":"FOUND","303":"See Other","303_CLASS":"3xx","303_MESSAGE":"The response to the request can be found under another URI using the GET method.","303_NAME":"SEE_OTHER","304":"Not Modified","304_CLASS":"3xx","304_MESSAGE":"Indicates that the resource has not been modified since t